        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-02-16T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-02-16T04:00:00-05:00" n="862" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d862">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">125.461/2–1646: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Smyth</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-02-16T16:00:00+07:00">February 16, 1946—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received February 17—5:39 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>314. Reopening of consular offices Manchuria (Dept’s 283, Feb 13<note n="11" xml:id="d862fn11">Not printed.</note> and Embassy’s 193, Jan [30]). Vice
                    Minister Foreign Affairs Liu Chieh informed me today that (sent Dept 314,
                    repeated Shanghai 104), while Foreign Office would like to have our consular
                    officers return to Manchuria, under present conditions in Manchuria, it would
                    not be practicable for the time being.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Smyth</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
